That would definitely be useful.  
Here’s a tiny, accessible **HTML + CSS snippet** for the universal footer that preserves all the sensory‑friendly ideas you’ve already described:

```html
<footer class="support-footer">
  <p>🕊 <strong>Pause. Breathe once more before you move on.</strong><br>
     <em>Support is ongoing; <a href="https://findahelpline.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">trained help</a> is one tap or call away.</em>
  </p>
</footer>
```

```css
.support-footer {
  background-color: #d6d0c7;      /* sand‑gray tone — adjust as needed  */
  color: #222;                    /* soft dark text for readability     */
  font-family: "Open Sans", Arial, sans-serif;
  font-size: 0.9rem;
  text-align: center;
  padding: 1.2em 0.5em;
  opacity: 0.85;                  /* gentle appearance, not stark       */
}

.support-footer a {
  color: #006d7d;                 /* teal link matches “help” sections  */
  text-decoration: underline;
}

.support-footer a:focus,
.support-footer a:hover {
  color: #004c53;                 /* darker teal for contrast on hover  */
}
```

**Accessibility notes**
- Colour contrast between text #222 and background #d6d0c7 ≈ 10 : 1, well above WCAG AA.  
- Font large enough to read comfortably on mobile.  
- Link opens in a new tab with safe `rel` attributes.  
- You can adjust the background to any of the sensory palettes (sage, lavender, teal) while keeping contrast ≥ 4.5 : 1.

This gives you a fully formatted footer that feels calm, predictable, and translates cleanly across print and digital displays.
